<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
    <!--
        The head is where we contain all of our metadata, or data about our data.
    -->
    <head>
            <!-- The viewport is a HTML5 feature that allows us to set the viewport
                 It is a part of responsive design.
                 width=device-width has the page automatically match the devices width.
                 initial-scale=1.0 sets the initial zoom level for when the page first loads.
             -->
            <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
            <!-- The title is what is going to appear in the browser tab. -->
            <title>About Me, Harvey Hill</title>
            <!-- charset tells the browser what character set the page will be using. -->
            <meta charset="UTF-8">
            <!-- The description is just that, a description of what your page is about. -->
            <meta name="description" content="HTML, CSS, and JS Examples for Revature Associates.">
            <!-- Keywords are used by search engines to help identify what your page is relevant to. -->
            <meta name="keywords" content="HTML,CSS,JavaScript">
            <!-- The author is who made the page. -->
            <meta name="author" content="Harvey Hill">
        <!-- CSS -->
            <!-- 
                CSS can be incorporated into your page three ways. External, Internal, and Inline. 
            -->
            <!-- This links to an external stylesheet -->
            <link rel="stylesheet" href="..\css\BasicCSS.css">
            <!-- This is an internal stylesheet -->
            <style>
                h6 {
                    color:blueviolet;
                }
                body {
                    background-color: white;
                }
            </style>
        <!-- JavaScript -->
            <!-- 
                JavaScript can be incorporated into your page also in two ways, 
                External, and Internal. Internal javascript should be placed after 
                the body tags. HTML is loaded in order, if you place it before the
                body depending on what is being executed, it can cause errors.
             -->
             <!-- This links to a external javascript file. -->
             <script src="..\js\BasicJS.js"></script>
    </head>
    <!-- 
        The body is intended to contain the visible parts of the page. 
        It is possible to put visible elements outside of the body, but
        it isn't considered good practice to do so.
    -->
    <body>
        <!-- 
            This is a Element, which is made up of a opening and closing tag, 
            and everything in between. The opening tag itself contains an 
            attribute of id. 
        -->
        <h6 id="hello">Hi</h6>
        <!-- 
            We can have block and inline elements.
            This one is a block element, which starts on a new line, and has 
            a width that stretches all the way to the left or right.
        -->
        <div class="Blockelement" >
            <p>
                <!-- 
                    This is an inline element, it doesn't start on a new line, 
                    and only uses as much width as needed.  
                -->
                Hello <span class="inlineelement">World</span>!!!
            </p>
        </div>
    </body>
    <!-- This is an example of internal javaScript. -->
    <script>
            document.querySelector("#hello").innerHTML = "Hello World!";
     </script>
</html>
